A commonly heard criticism is that ‘they have no alternative’, i.e. are not offering a precise
and integrated alternative political and social program. This in fact may reflect their new
approach to politics. The main demand is indeed not always for specifics, though that can
occasionally be part of a consensus platform (such as ‘abandoning the debt for developing
countries’), more importantly is the underlying philosophy, that ‘another world is possible’,
but that what is most important is not asking for specific alternative, but rather for an open
process of world governance that is not governed by the power politics and private interests of
the elite, but determined by all the people in an autonomous fashion that recognized the wide
diversity of desired futures. Thus, in that sense, the 'aim' of the alterglobalisation movement is
nothing else than a demand for a new 'organisation' of the world, based on the
P2P principles.<ref>'''the P2P principles of the alterglobalisation movement'''<br />
